('business:3-5-motivation-and-retention:match:64f6cd73', 'business', 'business:3-5-motivation-and-retention', '3.5 Motivation and Retention', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Performance-Related Pay”?", "options": ["The encouragement given to workers to work well, making them feel responsible, fulfilled and happy.", "When workers choose to stay employed in a business rather than leaving to work elsewhere.", "A system where workers receive extra pay based on how well they perform against a measurable target.", "The quality of the physical workplace and its social climate, including how workers are treated and whether they feel respected."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Performance-Related Pay” means: A system where workers receive extra pay based on how well they perform against a measurable target."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:d7ffe763', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "What is NOT a benefit to a golfing equipment retailer of training its sales assistants?", "options": ["To help staff give advice on which golf clubs to buy", "To increase the sales of golf umbrellas and waterproof clothing", "To motivate staff to assist customers who are trying on golf shoes", "To reduce the time it takes to make golf bags and golf trolleys"], "hint": "Think carefully about what a retailer does vs. what a manufacturer does.", "starter": "The answer is D because a retailer sells products — it does not..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> A retailer sells golf products — it does not manufacture them. Training sales assistants would not reduce manufacturing time because retail staff have no role in production.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Helping staff give advice on products IS a genuine benefit of training retail staff — it improves the quality of customer service.</li><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Better-trained staff can upsell related products (umbrellas, clothing), increasing revenue — this IS a benefit.</li><li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Training can motivate staff and improve their engagement with customers — this IS a benefit.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "D — To reduce the time it takes to make golf bags and golf trolleys. A retailer sells products; it does not manufacture them, so training sales assistants has no impact on production time."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:1cc408fa', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "Which one of the following is a disadvantage of using on-the-job training to train three new sales assistants?", "options": ["Likely to be more expensive than sending the employees on a training course", "Motorists may experience lower standards of customer service", "No petrol can be sold while the training takes place", "The employees will be trained on different equipment to that at the garage"], "caseStudy": "The manager of a petrol station uses on-the-job training to train new employees.", "hint": "Think about what can go wrong when an untrained person is serving real customers during training.", "starter": "The answer is B because when a trainee is serving real customers..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B</h5><p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> A trainee serving real customers may make mistakes or be slow, leading to lower quality customer service — motorists may experience poor service as a result.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> On-the-job training is generally cheaper than off-the-job (no external course fees or travel costs).</li><li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Petrol CAN still be sold during on-the-job training — the trainee is working while learning, meaning the business continues to operate.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> On-the-job training takes place at the actual workplace using the actual equipment — so trainees ARE trained on the correct equipment.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "B — Motorists may experience lower standards of customer service because a trainee who is still learning may make mistakes or be slow when serving real customers at the petrol station."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:059b1e4c', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "Which of the following is NOT a form of staff development?", "options": ["Academic qualifications", "Apprenticeships", "Induction", "Vocational qualifications"], "hint": "Staff development is long-term. Which of these options is short-term and about introducing a new worker to the business?", "starter": "The answer is C because induction is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Induction is a form of training — it is short-term and designed to introduce a new employee to the business and workplace. It is NOT staff development.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Academic qualifications (e.g. degrees) ARE a form of long-term staff development.</li><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Apprenticeships ARE a form of staff development — long-term programmes leading to qualifications.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Vocational qualifications ARE a form of staff development — job-specific long-term learning.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "C — Induction is NOT a form of staff development. It is a short-term form of training that introduces a new employee to the workplace, colleagues, and health and safety procedures — not a long-term development programme."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:6ba4a028', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "One benefit to Gina of staff development is:", "options": ["Higher profits", "Increased retention of farm workers", "More opportunities for promotion", "The animals will be better cared for"], "caseStudy": "Gina is an employee on a dairy farm.", "hint": "The question asks about a benefit to GINA — the employee — not to the farm business.", "starter": "The answer is C because staff development gives Gina..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Staff development helps Gina gain qualifications and skills that could lead to promotion — a direct personal benefit to the employee.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Higher profits is a benefit to the dairy farm (the business), not to Gina personally.</li><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Increased retention is a benefit to the business — it means the farm keeps its workers, not something that directly benefits Gina.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Better animal care is an operational outcome for the farm — not a personal benefit to Gina as an individual employee.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "C — More opportunities for promotion. Staff development helps Gina gain new qualifications and skills, making her more eligible for promotion to a more senior role with higher pay — a direct personal benefit."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:2a27c899', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "What is the most likely reason for this digital communication training?", "options": ["The company is trying to reduce employee retention", "The company needs to reduce the productivity of its sales staff", "The company wants workers to enjoy using social media during their breaks", "The company wishes to encourage more of its workforce to work from home"], "caseStudy": "A telesales company has arranged digital communication training for all relevant employees.", "hint": "Think about what digital communication enables — remote working requires digital tools to communicate effectively.", "starter": "The answer is D because digital communication skills allow employees to..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: D</h5><p><strong>Why D is correct:</strong> Digital communication tools (video calls, emails, messaging platforms) are essential for remote working. A telesales company training staff in digital communication is most likely preparing them to work effectively from home.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Businesses want to increase retention (keep staff), not reduce it.</li><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Businesses train staff to increase productivity, not reduce it.</li><li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Social media for personal use during breaks is not a business training priority and would be an unusual reason to arrange formal training.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "D — The company wishes to encourage more of its workforce to work from home. Digital communication training equips telesales staff with the skills needed to communicate effectively with colleagues and customers remotely."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:ff62252a', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "The percentage change in the training costs is approximately equal to:", "options": ["–20.6%", "–17.1%", "17.1%", "20.6%"], "caseStudy": "A firm has changed the way it trains its employees. Instead of using off-the-job training (£82,000) it now uses on-the-job training (£68,000).", "hint": "Percentage change = (New − Old) ÷ Old × 100. The original (old) cost is off-the-job: £82,000.", "starter": "Percentage change = (68,000 − 82,000) ÷ 82,000 × 100 = ..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B — −17.1%</h5><p><strong>Calculation:</strong></p><ul><li>Change = £68,000 − £82,000 = −£14,000</li><li>Percentage change = −14,000 ÷ 82,000 × 100 = −17.07% ≈ −17.1%</li></ul><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A (−20.6%):</strong> This is calculated using the new cost as the denominator (14,000 ÷ 68,000 × 100) — incorrect. Always divide by the original value.</li><li><strong>C (17.1%):</strong> Correct calculation but wrong sign — costs have decreased, not increased.</li><li><strong>D (20.6%):</strong> Wrong calculation and wrong sign.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "B — −17.1%. Percentage change = (68,000 − 82,000) ÷ 82,000 × 100 = −14,000 ÷ 82,000 × 100 ≈ −17.1%. The negative sign shows costs have decreased."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:cc8fa9d0', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "Which of the following is a benefit to a business of using off-the-job training?", "options": ["Large numbers of employees can be trained at the same time", "Likely to be cheaper than on-the-job training", "The training can take place while the employee is working", "Workers need to be paid for time spent doing off-the-job training"], "hint": "Think about what off-the-job training can do that individual on-the-job training cannot.", "starter": "The answer is A because off-the-job training at a venue or training centre can..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A</h5><p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> Off-the-job training at a college or training centre can accommodate multiple employees simultaneously — unlike on-the-job training which is typically one-on-one.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>B — Wrong:</strong> Off-the-job training is typically more expensive than on-the-job training due to course fees, travel, and accommodation costs.</li><li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> This describes on-the-job training, not off-the-job training.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> This is a disadvantage of off-the-job training, not a benefit — the business still pays wages while workers are not producing output.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "A — Large numbers of employees can be trained at the same time. Off-the-job training venues (e.g. colleges, training centres) can train groups of employees simultaneously, which on-the-job training (typically one-on-one) cannot achieve."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:exam:5ed2aba0', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "One benefit to a hospital of encouraging staff development is:", "options": ["Increased skill shortages", "Improved patient care", "Lower morale of doctors and nurses", "More medical staff can be employed"], "hint": "Think about what happens when hospital staff are better trained and qualified — what does that mean for the people they care for?", "starter": "The answer is B because when hospital staff develop their skills..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: B</h5><p><strong>Why B is correct:</strong> When hospital staff develop their skills through qualifications and professional development, the quality of their work improves — leading directly to better care for patients.</p><p><strong>Why the others are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A — Wrong:</strong> Staff development reduces skill shortages (by building skills internally), not increases them.</li><li><strong>C — Wrong:</strong> Development should improve morale (workers feel valued), not lower it.</li><li><strong>D — Wrong:</strong> Staff development is about improving the skills of existing staff, not directly leading to hiring more staff.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": "B — Improved patient care. When hospital staff such as doctors and nurses undertake professional development and gain higher qualifications, their knowledge and clinical skills improve — leading to better treatment outcomes and higher quality care for patients."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:4a06c2c1', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is the main difference between training and development?", "options": ["Training is long-term and development is short-term", "Training is job-specific and short-term; development is about long-term potential", "Development only involves on-the-job activities", "Training always leads to a qualification"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: Training is short-term and focused on a specific job or task. Development is longer-term and about growing the overall potential of the worker for future roles."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:a0784f89', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is a feature of off-the-job training?", "options": ["The worker continues to produce goods or services whilst training", "It is a cheaper way of training workers than paying for them to go on courses", "Workers are trained in a college or training centre away from where they do the work", "It never leads to a qualification for the worker"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: Off-the-job training takes place away from the employee''s normal duties — at an external venue such as a college or training centre. A is on-the-job, B is wrong (off-the-job is more expensive), D is false (off-the-job often leads to qualifications)."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:fa08bfe9', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is NOT a benefit to a golfing equipment retailer of training its sales assistants?", "options": ["To help staff give advice on which golf clubs to buy", "To increase the sales of golf umbrellas and waterproof clothing", "To motivate staff to assist customers who are trying on golf shoes", "To reduce the time it takes to make golf bags and golf trolleys"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct: A retailer doesn''t make golf bags — it sells them. Training sales assistants would not reduce manufacturing time because retail staff don''t manufacture products. A, B, and C are all genuine benefits of training retail staff."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:93ac8f1d', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is induction training?", "options": ["Training to help workers gain a vocational qualification", "Long-term development to realise a worker''s potential", "Training to introduce a new worker to the business and workplace", "On-the-job training delivered by an experienced colleague"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: Induction training is specifically for new employees to help them settle into the workplace — meeting colleagues, learning health and safety rules, and understanding the culture of the business. It is NOT about teaching job skills."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:21059a6e', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is a disadvantage of using on-the-job training to train new sales assistants at a petrol station?", "options": ["Likely to be more expensive than sending the employees on a training course", "Motorists may experience lower standards of customer service", "No petrol can be sold while the training takes place", "The employees will be trained on different equipment to that at the garage"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: A trainee serving real customers may make mistakes, leading to lower service quality. A is wrong — on-the-job is cheaper. C is wrong — petrol can still be sold. D is wrong — on-the-job uses the actual workplace equipment."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:059b1e4c', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is NOT a form of staff development?", "options": ["Academic qualifications", "Apprenticeships", "Induction", "Vocational qualifications"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: Induction is a form of training — it is short-term and designed to introduce a new worker to the business. Staff development (academic qualifications, apprenticeships, vocational qualifications) is long-term and aimed at realising the worker''s future potential."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:9539b4f4', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is a feature of professional development?", "options": ["It is a kind of short-term training", "It is designed to realise the potential of a worker in the long-term interests of the business and the worker", "It is designed to improve the skills of the worker to do a specific task", "It usually involves on-the-job training only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: Professional development is long-term and is about realising the potential of the worker — it may lead to vocational or academic qualifications. A and C describe training. D is false — professional development often includes off-the-job study at college or university."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:21da89ac', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "One benefit to Gina, an employee on a dairy farm, of staff development is:", "options": ["Higher profits for the farm", "Increased retention of farm workers", "More opportunities for promotion", "The animals will be better cared for"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct: Staff development benefits the individual worker — gaining qualifications and skills may lead to promotion opportunities. A and B are benefits to the business, not the employee. D relates to animal welfare, not a personal benefit to Gina."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:5ed2aba0', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "One benefit to a hospital of encouraging staff development is:", "options": ["Increased skill shortages", "Improved patient care", "Lower morale of doctors and nurses", "More medical staff can be employed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: When hospital staff are developed through training and qualifications, their skills improve — leading directly to improved patient care. A is the opposite of a benefit. C is wrong — development improves morale. D is unrelated to development."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:d2048c4f', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following statements about apprenticeships is true?", "options": ["A vocational qualification is specific to a particular type of job", "An academic qualification prepares a worker for work in a specific business", "An apprenticeship is offered to senior managers who want to develop their skills further", "An apprenticeship involves only studying at university"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Correct: Vocational qualifications are job-specific — they relate to a particular occupation. B is wrong — academic qualifications are more general. C is wrong — apprenticeships are aimed at developing workers in a role, not exclusively senior managers. D is wrong — apprenticeships combine workplace training with college study."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:cd5a41a2', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A firm switches from off-the-job training (costing £82,000) to on-the-job training (costing £68,000). What is the approximate percentage change in training costs?", "options": ["–20.6%", "–17.1%", "17.1%", "20.6%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct: Percentage change = (68,000 − 82,000) / 82,000 × 100 = −14,000 / 82,000 × 100 ≈ −17.1%. The negative sign shows a decrease in cost."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:mcq:cc8fa9d0', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of the following is a benefit to a business of using off-the-job training?", "options": ["Large numbers of employees can be trained at the same time", "Likely to be cheaper than on-the-job training", "The training can take place while the employee is working", "Workers need to be paid for time spent doing off-the-job training"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Correct: Off-the-job training at a venue can accommodate larger groups simultaneously — a key advantage over one-on-one on-the-job training. B is wrong — off-the-job is more expensive. C describes on-the-job training. D is a disadvantage, not a benefit."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:d4b3f376', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Induction training is designed to teach new workers the specific skills they need to do their job."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. Induction training is about introducing new employees to the workplace, colleagues, culture, and health and safety procedures — not teaching job-specific skills. Examiners frequently penalise students who confuse induction with skills training."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:e677b3a5', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "On-the-job training is generally cheaper than off-the-job training for a business."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. On-the-job training has no travel, accommodation, or external course fees. The trainee also continues to produce goods or services during training, meaning the business still earns money."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:ec19ebe9', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Off-the-job training always leads to a qualification for the worker."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. Off-the-job training does not always lead to a qualification — it depends on the type of course. However, it is more likely to lead to qualifications than on-the-job training."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:e903dd65', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A disadvantage of professional development for a business is that once workers are better qualified, they may find it easier to secure jobs at other firms."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. This is a genuine retention risk for businesses. After investing in development, a more qualified worker may leave for a higher-paying role elsewhere, meaning the business does not get a return on its investment."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:cce4a915', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Apprenticeships are a form of staff development, not just a recruitment method."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. On this specification, apprenticeships appear in Section 3.6 as staff development. They involve developing existing employees who are already paid a wage, not just recruiting new ones cheaply."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:48f8f43e', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "On-the-job training is suitable for all types of jobs, including those with significant safety risks."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. On-the-job training is not appropriate for safety-critical roles (e.g. cabin crew, surgeons) because mistakes made during training could endanger lives. Off-the-job simulation is required in these cases."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:bd0f61c7', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Development is more short-term and practical than training."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. It is the other way around. Training is short-term and practical; development is long-term and often includes both theoretical and practical learning to build the worker''s overall potential."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:97d53e8f', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A benefit of on-the-job training is that the trainee produces goods and services while learning, so the firm earns money during the training process."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. Because the trainee is working while learning, the business does not lose all of that worker''s productive output — a key financial advantage over off-the-job training where the worker is absent from their role entirely."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:c937b73c', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Academic qualifications are specific to a particular job role."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. Vocational qualifications are job-specific. Academic qualifications (e.g. GCSEs, A Levels, degrees) are more general and transferable across many different careers."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:3420e98e', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Businesses may train workers to solve skill shortages if the specialist labour they need cannot be found externally."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. If the market doesn''t supply enough skilled workers, businesses can train existing employees to fill those gaps internally — for example, training technicians to become fully qualified engineers."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:tf:cce82d56', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The quality of on-the-job training depends on the communication skills and ability of the trainer."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. If the trainer has poor communication skills or bad habits, the trainee will learn them too. The quality of the training is only as good as the person delivering it — a key disadvantage of on-the-job training."}'::jsonb),
('business:3-6-training-and-development:learn:ee7b5345', 'business', 'business:3-6-training-and-development', '3.6 Training and Development', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Key Terms & Official Definitions", "reading": "<p>These are the essential terms you must know for the exam. Learn the distinction between each one carefully — examiners regularly test whether students can tell them apart.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Training:</strong> Short-term learning focused on improving a worker''s ability to do a specific job or task.</li>\n    <li><strong>Development:</strong> Long-term learning focused on growing a worker''s overall potential for future roles.</li>\n    <li><strong>On-the-job training:</strong> Training that takes place at the workplace while the employee is doing their job.</li>\n    <li><strong>Off-the-job training:</strong> Training that takes place away from the normal job, either on-site or at an external venue.</li>\n    <li><strong>Induction training:</strong> Training to introduce a new employee to the business, workplace, colleagues, and job role.</li>\n    <li><strong>Apprenticeship:</strong> A long-term development programme (typically 2–4 years) combining on-the-job and off-the-job learning, leading to a vocational qualification.</li>\n    <li><strong>Professional development:</strong> Long-term development of a worker through vocational or academic qualifications to realise their future potential.</li>\n    <li><strong>Vocational qualification:</strong> A job-specific qualification gained through a mix of practical and classroom learning (e.g. NVQ, Cambridge Technical).</li>\n    <li><strong>Academic qualification:</strong> A more general, theory-based qualification (e.g. GCSEs, A Levels, degrees).</li>\n    <li><strong>Productivity:</strong> Output per worker — a measure of how efficiently employees produce goods or services.</li>\n    <li><strong>Skills shortage:</strong> A situation where businesses cannot recruit workers with the skills they need.</li>\n    <li><strong>Retention:</strong> Keeping workers employed rather than them leaving to work elsewhere.</li>\n  </ul>", "question": "What is the key difference between training and development?", "options": ["Training is job-specific and short-term; development is long-term and broader", "They are exactly the same thing", "Training only happens off-the-job; development only happens on-the-job", "Development is for new employees only; training is for experienced staff only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Training focuses on improving performance in the current job, in the short term. Development is broader and longer-term, focused on growing a worker''s overall future potential."}'::jsonb)
